<TEXT>
the bush administration is pressing el 
salvadors president alfredo cristiani for progress on 
investigating the murders of six jesuit priests the white house 
said tuesday 
presidential chief of staff john sununu raised the matter with 
cristiani in a meeting monday in san jose costa rica where both 
were attending the presidential inauguration of rafael calderon 
said white house press secretary marlin fitzwater 
nine salvadoran military men have been accused of murdering the 
priests on nov 16 
sununu emphasized that this is a serious matter for the us 
that must be properly addressed and he said that prosecution of 
this case would have a significant impact in america fitzwater 
told reporters 
the spokesman said cristiani had asked for the meeting 
fitzwater did not say that us aid to el salvador would be cut 
if the salvadoran government fails to pursue the case but he did 
say that sununu underscored with cristiani the growing reluctance 
in congress to approve additional aid while the case is stalled 
secretary of state james a baker iii recently told a 
congressional committee that us assistance will be affected by 
how the case is handled 
the administration and everyone in america is concerned about 
the prosecution of the murders and that obviously would have an 
impact on american attitudes fitzwater said when asked whether 
the administration would back away from its request for 90 million 
in military aid for el salvador next year 
he said sununu and cristiani talked about the overall problems 
of the aid bill the overall attitude in congress and the status of 
the investigation 
a democratic congressional report this month said the 
investigation of the case has come to a virtual standstill due to a 
reluctance by the salvadoran government to implicate its military 
the state department said monday that the us embassy in san 
salvador is looking into reports that a log book and diary of one 
defendant col guillermo benavides is missing 
benavides has been accused of ordering the slayings of the 
jesuits who were accused by rightists of sympathizing with leftist 
salvadoran rebels 
columnists rowland evans and robert novak said in a column 
appearing in wednesday newspapers they had interviewed benavides 
for 2 hours and he denied all knowledge of the massacre saying 
it was a complete surprise to me 
three lieutenants accused in the case are among those who have 
accused benavides of ordering the killings they reportedly have 
said their orders came from benavides but there are now private 
reports from the high command that the lieutenants are withdrawing 
their accusations against him the columnists wrote 
benevides was quoted as saying two of the lieutenants had been 
under his command for only two days and he gave them no orders and 
all his orders to the third had to pass through the staff of the 
military school he commanded 
us officials trying to move the case along had encouraged 
the judge in the case to follow up such leads as the colonels log 
and diary boucher said 
the administration has avoided directly criticizing cristiani 
but the sununu meeting is evidence of increasing us pressure on 
him to make sure the investigation gets back on track and is 
successfully concluded 
we take him at his word that hes trying to prosecute this to 
the best of his ability fitzwater said adding in reference to 
the missing evidence there are these complicating matters 
</TEXT>
