<TEXT>
a highfashion show of french dolls wearing postwar 
couture outfits has been brought back from the united states after 
44 years in exile 
called le theatre de la mode the exhibition of 171 dolls in 
spectacular parisian settings will be presented thursday at the 
musee des arts de la mode in a wing of the louvre 
created by top couturiers and artists the exhibition created a 
sensation in 1945 in france then in england and the united states 
the following year 
with clothes by designers such as gres balenciaga and balmain 
and sets by the likes of jean cocteau the exhibit showed the world 
paris remained a fashion leader despite its wartime hardships 
having been lost for decades the dolls were traced to a 
museum in goldendale wash 
they were brought back to be refurbished and displayed thanks to 
a chance discovery and the perseverance of susan train parisbased 
editor of vogue magazine 
it was like a miracle said train who first heard in 1983 
that the doll collection was at the maryhill museum 
id heard about the beautiful dolls before but nobody seemed 
to know where they were said train 
then she was contacted by stanley garfinkel a history professor 
at kent state university in ohio who stumbled across the 
collection during research 
train consulted fashion industry leaders such as pierre berge 
president of yves saint laurent and jacques mouclier head of the 
chambre syndicale fashion guild 
everyone was excited by the discovery and we decided to have 
the show here if maryhill agreed said train traveling to 
goldendale she found many of the 27inchhigh dolls in good 
condition 
she won an agreement to let the dolls return to france 
temporarily 
after closing in paris on sept 9 the show will move in 
december to the costume institute of new yorks metropolitan museum 
before the dolls return to maryhill 
in 1992 they are scheduled to be shown in tokyo 
ive been living and breathing the dolls said train who 
enlisted the few original creators still alive to help reconstitute 
the 1945 show 
she also persuaded writers like former vogue editor edmonde 
charlesroux and historians garfinkel and herbert lottman to write 
chapters of an accompanying book 
of the postwar couturiers only mmes gres and carven are 
living but were lucky to have two of the original setmakers 
andre beaurepaire and jeandenis malcles said train 
before the show opened the museums workrooms and galleries 
bustled with artisans putting final touches on the dolls and 
12foothigh sets 
it was like an archaeological puzzle to put heads arms and 
legs together said train 
she pointed out a gown with a tulle drape and silk cord basque 
waist 
that was just a crumpled rag when we first saw it she said 
but nadine gasc a curator of the fashion museum figured out how 
the original looked 
the costumes ranged from tweed suits to satin ball gowns 
its amazing how the dolls began to get their personalities 
back when the experts started working on them train said 
every detail was perfect from gloves to platformsoled shoes 
every hair of the elaborate period coiffures was in place as styled 
by alexandre todays most famous hairdresser 
imagine going 40 years without a coiffeur said train 
miniature pins were used to curl the dolls locks 
conceived by robert ricci son of couturiere nina ricci working 
with lucien lelong head of the chambre syndicale the show was 
intended to raise money for french war victims 
it proved a brilliant success and stands today as a document of 
postwar fashion and art 
train said the exhibition ended up at maryhill after being kept 
in a san francisco department store following a museum show there 
moving the whole thing back to france was apparently too 
expensive so with french approval in 1952 it was sent to the 
maryhill 
the accompanying book due to appear in english in december 
fills in background about the period and its fashions 
nadine gascs chapter points out the nearmiracle of creating 
such a collection at a time when paris was exhausted by the 
occupation food was scarce not to mention couture materials 
the nazis tried several times to transport french couture 
lock stock and barrel to germany she said but finally an 
accord was reached whereby 60 houses could continue operating in 
france during the war with small allotments of fabric 
</TEXT>
