pete rose awaiting sentencing on tax charges 
is no longer considered a publicity coup by some charities 
several charities have dropped plans to use the banished 
ballplayer in publicizing their causes his spokeswoman barbara 
pinzka said monday 
some charitable organizations decided that despite the 
potential benefits of having pete work with their organizations 
they were concerned about negative publicity she said there 
have been three or four cancellations along those lines 
banned from baseball last year for gambling the former 
cincinnati reds manager admitted cheating on his taxes by failing 
to report 354968 over four years he could receive up to six 
months and jail and 500000 in fines 
no sentencing date has been set 
rose is living at his winter home in plant city fla and has 
several autograph appearances and charity golf tournaments 
scheduled for the next two months pinzka said he also is doing a 
weekly radio sports show in cincinnati 
