<TEXT>
selmas first black schools superintendent 
resigned monday and said he would drop his 10 million racial 
discrimination suit against the city and the school board in return 
for a cash settlement 
in announcing his resignation norward roussell cited the stress 
of the turmoil surrounding his case since the school board voted 
late last year to dismiss him 
roussell did not disclose the amount of the settlement but said 
it was close to what he would have received if his threeyear 
69500ayear contract had been renewed about 208500 he said 
the settlement agreement would be effective when i get the 
money 
the december vote by the whitecontrolled school board not to 
renew roussells contract expiring june 30 sparked 
nearcontinuous protests by blacks some of whom were arrested 
during demonstrations 
roussell sued the city and the school board claiming racial 
discrimination was behind the boards vote the board said it voted 
to dismiss him because of his management style 
in his resignation statement roussell said he decided to exit 
early so he and his family could go on with their lives without 
continually having to deal with the stress related to the current 
situation in selma 
people are protesting because they want quality education for 
their children roussell said in a telephone interview from his 
home monday night this protest has never been about me it is 
not something i asked people to do 
roussell said he had plans for his future but he declined to 
discuss them 
