<DOCNO> AP900508-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
six army inventory centers lost control of 
more than 328 million in payments to contractors and in some 
cases overpayments and errors in accounting went uncorrected for a 
year or more congressional investigators say 
the general accounting office in a study released monday said 
a review of selected payments showed the army did not take prompt 
action to collect millions of dollars in overpayments made to 
contractors and did not correct thousands of bookkeeping errors 
it said one yearold 28 million overpayment wasnt collected 
until it was brought to the attention of defense department 
personnel by the gao an investigative arm of congress 
in another instance the gao found that more than a year elapsed 
before the army detected a 307000 duplicate payment to a 
contractor the study said 
the report noted that the lack of accuracy tied up army funds 
which could be used to meet other army requirements if not 
collected promptly these overpayments can be considered 
interestfree loans to contractors and may be lost in case of 
contractor bankruptcy 
although army regulations require that immediate corrective 
action be taken to resolve such problems we found that in many 
cases the subordinate commands do not initiate followup actions for 
a year or more to resolve outstanding negative balances the 
study said 
the gao study involved a review of the army materiel commands 
control procedures over what is formally known as negative 
unliquidated obligations or ulos related to the purchases of 
supplies and equipment these result when the recorded expenditure 
exceeds the amount obligated the gao said 
the army materiel command has six subordinate commands 
nationwide through which it purchases stocks and distributes 
billions of dollars worth of supplies it performs this task for 
army units other military services and foreign governments 
as of last sept 30 records showed about 4500 negative ulo 
balances totaling 328 million the study said 
our analysis of the negative ulo balances totaling about 49 
million show that 47 of the balances valued at over 23 million 
were more than six months old the study said coordination 
problems between the commands and other department of defense 
organizations caused these delays in resolving the negative 
balances 
because regulations dont require the disclosure of such 
problems army headquarters personnel did not know the 
magnitude of the negative balances the report said 
most of the negative ulos occurred because a contractor 
was paid too much or information on an obligation payment or 
collection transaction was inaccurately or incompletely 
processed the study said 
of the 49 million in negative ulos we reviewed in detail 
76 million was caused by overpayments 238 million was due to 
processing errors and 27 million was related to other causes 
the study said in addition the causes for 18 million could not 
be determined 
also the study said the government employees responsible for 
making the overpayments to contractors are personally liable for 
any overpayments that are not covered unless the comptroller 
general who heads the gao relieves them of that liability 
the report said 
in its comment on the report defense department officials 
agreed that the reports findings were serious and that they 
reflect a systematic dod problem 
the department agreed to take remedial action along the lines 
recommended in the report 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

