<TEXT>
consumer prices rose a record 863 percent in 
third world countries last year spurred by a 350 percent rise in 
latin america the international monetary fund reports 
the united states the worlds largest economy was a little 
above the average of industrial countries at 48 percent 
among 22 industrial countries the rise was only 45 percent up 
from 34 percent in 1988 the imf said monday the increases ranged 
from 11 percent in the netherlands to 208 percent in iceland 
japan had 23 percent and west germany 28 percent 
the imf gets figures from its member countries but calculates 
them on its own basis to make them comparable so rates for 
individual nations sometimes differ from those published by 
governments themselves 
latin american average prices were heavily increased by runaway 
inflation in two of the areas most important countries argentina 
at 3079 percent and brazil at 1287 percent that meant argentine 
consumers were paying roughly 30 times as much for the same basket 
of goods at the end of 1989 as at the beginning of the year 
peru had an even higher rate 3398 percent 
mexico which adopted a strict austerity program dropped to 20 
percent from 114 percent in 1988 
the fund classifies 130 of its members as developing 
countries including those in eastern europe the soviet union 
does not belong and the fund gives no figures for it 
for its seven european members outside the industrial group the 
inflation rate rose in 1989 to an average 232 percent largely 
because of yugoslavias 1239 percent and polands 244 percent an 
imf official said polands inflation has dropped sharply this year 
because of the new nonmarxist governments shock program to shift 
away from communism toward a market system 
annual figures for africa and the middle east were incomplete 
many middle east countries have not been reporting in recent years 
among those that have israels inflation rate rose to 202 percent 
last year from 163 percent in 1988 and egypts climbed to 213 
percent from 177 percent a year earlier 
africas average appeared steady 189 percent in 1988 and 212 
percent in the third quarter of 1989 that average masked a wide 
range from zambias 186 percent inflation in october to small 
price reductions in several countries including chad togo and the 
central african republic 
only asias average showed a decline in the inflation rate for 
21 countries there the annual increase dropped to 102 percent last 
year from 118 percent in 1988 chinas rate declined to 163 
percent from 207 percent and india fell from 94 percent in 1988 
to an annual rate of 62 percent in the third quarter of 1989 
