an arrangement under which more than 
13000 contra rebels are to disarm and be given land to work 
parallels in some ways an earlier episode in 20thcentury 
nicaraguan history 
in 1932 a newly elected civilian government uneasily 
coexisting with a strong military struck a peace pact with 
recalcitrant guerrillas 
in exchange for laying down their weapons the rebels of the 
1920s and 30s were promised a huge cooperative where they could 
farm and live among their own augusto cesar sandino the general 
of free men who fought against the us occupation of nicaragua 
for five years had cut a deal with the elected government of 
president juan bautista sacasa 
sandino and his army of peasants were granted about a fourth of 
the country to farm 
resentful of the pact and suspicious of the rebel generals 
intentions gen anastasio somoza who headed the national guard 
created by the united states had sandino killed on feb 21 1934 
less than two years later somoza seized power starting a 
43year dynasty that ended on july 19 1979 when the guerrillas of 
the sandinista national liberation front named after sandino 
seized control of a popular uprising and ousted somozas son also 
named anastasio 
now the usbacked contra rebels have cut a deal with the new 
government of president violeta barrios de chamorro in exchange for 
giving up their arms in a process that was to begin today 
mrs chamorro elected feb 25 and inaugurated last month is 
struggling to bring peace to a country that has seen nine years of 
war between the contras and the leftist sandinistas who continue 
to control the army 
in exchange for disarming the contras most of whom are 
peasants are to receive land in southern nicaragua where they can 
settle 
the contras had refused to fulfill a previous accord to lay down 
their arms saying they wanted gen humberto ortega brother of 
former president daniel ortega and a leader of the sandinista 
revolution removed as commander in chief of the armed forces 
the latest accord reached last friday makes no mention of that 
demand 
mrs chamorros government in a transition of power agreement 
signed in march allowed the sandinistas to keep control of the 
army in exchange for depoliticizing the body 
