<TEXT>
this university town has named a 
commissioner to oversee the welfare of some 60000 animals used in 
experiments here each year 
dr stuart wiles was named monday to the position of 
commissioner of laboratory animals established by the city council 
in june as part of the nations first city ordinance to protect 
animals used for research 
wiles a veterinarian will monitor harvard university the 
massachusetts institute of technology and about a dozen other 
academic and private firms that do about some 100 million per year 
in animal research 
this will keep scientists honest said gul agha who 
initiated the legislation four years ago when he was a researcher 
at mit 
its an excellent precedent because we have two of the most 
prestigious institutions in the country accepting accountability to 
the public agha who teaches computer science at the university 
of chicago at urbana said in a telephone interview 
the ordinance which covers all nonhuman vertebrates defines 
an experiment as any procedure a research institution conducts on a 
live animal institutions covered include schools colleges and 
diagnostic laboratories 
federal law covers dogs cats and monkeys but not reptiles 
amphibians mice rats and rabbits 
wiles job will be to ensure that researchers provide proper 
ventilation nourishment and other care to lab animals 
the commissioner has the right to make unannounced visits to 
research sites report infractions to the city manager conduct 
hearings and impose fines of 300 per day per violation 
there are a great many people concerned about the welfare of 
animals wiles said but its important to regulate not 
overregulate or place an unfair burden on the researchers 
