estonia today dropped the words 
soviet socialist from its name and adopted the republics old 
tricolor flag in place of the red banner of socialism as it took 
another step toward independence 
the estonian parliament without formally declaring 
independence reinstituted several paragraphs from the baltic 
republics 1938 constitution including an opening proclamation 
that estonia is an independent republic with the supreme state 
power vested in the people 
nationalist parliamentarians regard the move as another step in 
a phased march toward independence and not in itself a formal break 
with moscow 
the parliament also declared that the step in large part 
symbolic was intended as a show of solidarity with the sister 
baltic republics of lithuania and latvia which have declared full 
independence 
all three republics were forcibly annexed by the soviet union in 
1940 
the vote today was 73 in favor 14 against with two 
abstentions eight members present but not voting and eight 
absent the measure passed with three votes more than the required 
twothirds majority of the legislatures total membership 
minutes after the vote was taken in the estonian supreme soviet 
the red flag with its hammer and sickle was lowered from the roof 
of the ancient parliament building and a new flag with cornflower 
blue black and white stripes was raised in its place 
a small crowd gathered in the cobblestone square to see what 
would follow but there was no immediate attempt to cover the giant 
hammer and sickle crest that has adorned the front of the building 
for five decades 
estonia which in november 1988 became the first of the 15 
soviet republics to proclaim its sovereignty from moscow has taken 
repeated steps in recent months to establish a separate identity 
without provoking a confrontation with president mikhail s 
gorbachev over the issue of independence 
the nearby baltic republic of lithuania which declared 
independence on march 11 is now the target of an economic blockade 
in which the soviets have cut the flow of oil natural gas and 
other critical raw materials 
the third baltic republic latvia declared independence on may 
4 and is now waiting to hear whether gorbachev will impose 
sanctions similar to those he slapped on lithuania 
the estonian parliament today adopted a resolution 
congratulating latvia on declaring independence and declaring 
baltic solidarity 
we congratulate the latvian supreme soviet and the whole 
population of latvia on the occasion of adopting the independence 
declaration of the latvian republic said the statement which 
was broadcast on radio estonia and monitored by the british 
broadcasting corp in britain 
the path to our own statehood is not easy but we are 
convinced that here in the baltics acting together will arrive 
at a restoration of our independent states more fruitfully than if 
each were to struggle on its own the statement said 
tallinn deputy mart laar said estonia already is feeling the 
effects of the soviet oil and natural gas embargo against 
lithuania because a lithuanian refinery processes 50 percent of 
estonias gasoline 
the estonians have been trying for weeks to start talks with the 
kremlin leading toward eventual independence but moscow so far has 
refused 
the estonian independent an englishlanguage weekly in the 
capital of tallinn reported in its most recent edition that 
gorbachev adviser alexander yakovlev told estonian supreme soviet 
chairman arnold ruutel that no negotiations could start unless the 
parliament suspended a march 30 ruling that invalidated the soviet 
constitution on estonian territory 
the action today carried estonia a step further and said that 
dropping of soviet symbols was guided by the decision of march 
30 the law adopted today made the offical name the estonian 
republic 
ethnic estonians make of 64 percent of the overall population of 
15 million the ethnic russian minority makes up 30 percent 
</TEXT>
