<TEXT>
the ministry of industry has dismissed the 
director of the staterun oil monopoly blaming him for a 
disruption in supplies that has led to long lines at gas stations 
a ministry spokesman said today 
jerzy szewczyk was fired from his post as director of the 
central oil company for failing to predict a need to increase crude 
oil imports said the spokesman jan golab 
for the last week gas stations across poland have been plagued 
by long lines reminiscent of the chronic shortages during the 
former communist regime when gasoline had to be rationed 
the lines dwindled after the marketoriented policies of the new 
solidarityled government reduced demand by raising gasoline prices 
dramatically to match world market prices more closely 
golab said that due to a shortage of funds szewczyk had kept a 
relatively low supply of gas in poland and had not anticipated 
increased purchases last week as a result of two national holidays 
supplies to gas stations dried up causing long lines to appear 
and requiring rapid imports golab said 
the failure of the soviet union to meet its obligations in crude 
oil deliveries has also contributed to the disruption of gas 
supplies 
some soviet gasoline bound for poland is refined in lithuania 
moscow has sharply reduced oil supplies to the baltic republic as 
part of an economic blockade aimed at forcing the lithuanians to 
back off their declaration of independence 
the offical pap news agency reported that deliveries from the 
soviet union dropped by 10000 tons in april as a result of 
general problems in its economy and trade with poland 
polish newspapers reported today that the situation is likely to 
improve in the short term because tankers with foreign oil were 
either already docked or on their way to the baltic port of gdansk 
