<TEXT>
alexander plunket greene who with his wife mary 
quant helped revolutionize the british fashion scene for young 
people in the 1960s has died his family announced 
he died friday at age 57 his family reported monday no cause 
of death was stated 
plunket greene and mary quant met when they were both students 
at goldsmiths college of art in southeast london and they married 
in 1957 
in 1955 plunket greene and a friend archie mcnair had opened 
a fashion boutique called bazaar in the kings road in west 
londons chelsea district 
quant was initially the buyer for bazaar but with her husbands 
encouragement she began to sell her own trendsetting designs 
these included the miniskirt that became the symbol of britains 
swinging sixties 
the influence of the couple turned the kings road into the 
fashion mecca for young britons 
crowded with clothes boutiques and chic restaurants its 
sidewalks became a perpetual fashion show as young people flocked 
there to buy the latest styles and be seen wearing them the styles 
were widely copied abroad 
bazaar became one of the first stores to cater almost 
exclusively to the new generation of affluent young 
the couple opened a second store in the nearby knightsbridge 
district of london in 1961 and plunket greene opened a restaurant 
in the basement of the original kings road store 
tall witty elegant and sociable plunket greene in 1963 
expanded into the mass market with a new mary quant label ginger 
group and launched his wifes designs with considerable success in 
the united states 
during the 1970s he expanded the mary quant licences to include 
items such as bed linens carpets swim wear hosiery and jewelry 
and secured a place in the japanese market 
he is survived by his wife and their 19yearold son orlando 
</TEXT>
