<TEXT>
the easiest way for rep stephen solarz to 
become a millionaire is to quit his job ditto for rep dan 
rostenkowski 
solarz and rostenkowski both democrats are among 184 lawmakers 
eligible to put leftover campaign cash to personal use if they 
retire from the house by january 1993 
they can take the money and not run 
until 1979 members of congress were allowed to convert leftover 
campaign funds to personal use when they retired but congress 
voted that year to halt the practice for lawmakers elected after 
january 1980 
last year congress voted to totally ban the practice the 
measure however delayed the effective date of the prohibition to 
january 1993 giving those eligible more than two years to decide 
whether to retire and take the money 
the senate bars members from converting campaign funds but all 
members of congress are allowed to use their campaign accounts for 
political purposes after leaving office 
house members may keep whatever campaign funds they had as of 
nov 30 1989 about 40 million for the 184 house members covered 
by the clause 
sixty of the 184 members had at least 100000 in their campaign 
accounts at the cutoff date a handful had less than 5000 
one kentucky democrat william natcher is eligible but reported 
a zero campaign balance a month after the cutoff date 
most house members are reluctant to discuss whether the deadline 
will affect their political plans for 1992 saying they are 
concentrating on legislative business and the 1990 elections 
but the aging of many senior house members and redistricting as 
a result of the 1990 census has led to speculation that 1992 will 
be a high turnover year 
retirement in 1992 is going to be attractive to a lot of older 
members said william schneider a political analyst at the 
american enterprise institute 
older incumbents who see their safe districts shaken up by 
redistricting may be tempted to just retire and keep their 
campaign money schneider said of course theyll come up with 
any number of other public reasons for deciding not to run 
solarz is among the those whose futures could be affected by 
redistricting new york city probably will lose a congressional 
seat and solarz could end up in a race against a fellow incumbent 
perhaps democrat charles schumer 
but solarz who had a 15 million campaign war chest at the 
cutoff repeatedly has said he has no plans to retire before 1993 
and that he would not convert his campaign cash if defeated 
rostenkowski is unopposed this fall and many of his colleagues 
think the chicago lawmaker will retire after one more term he had 
1 million in campaign funds at the nov 30 1989 cutoff and has 
been vague about his plans 
were focusing on this years agenda and winning reelection 
in 1990 and then well worry about 1992 said rostenkowski 
spokesman jim jaffe 
rostenkowski has not said whether he would take his campaign 
funds with him if he left office before the deadline jaffe said 
but its the law that members can convert and he supports the 
law jaffe said 
a handful of those retiring from congress this year could 
convert their campaign funds to personal use 
one retiring member kansas republican robert whittaker has 
said he would not use his 500000plus in excess campaign money 
for personal purposes 
georgia democrat doug barnard who says his next house term will 
be his last has more than 500000 and has said he might convert 
some for personal use 
retiring rep bill frenzel a minnesota republican who has more 
than 300000 left plans to refund all 1989 and 1990 campaign 
contributions pay bills and give the remainder to other candidates 
most of the others who are eligible avoid the subject 
they dont like to advertise it because it just makes people 
angry schneider said 
once lawmakers retire they dont have to worry about whether 
such criticism will cost them votes 
former rep samuel stratton of new york wrote himself a check 
for nearly 200000 from campaign funds last year retired ohio 
republican rep delbert latta converted 123000 
missouri republican gene taylor closed his campaign account last 
year by giving 52000 to charity and 345000 to himself 
