<TEXT>
doubledigit mortgage rates and rising prices 
dampened existing home sales in many areas during the first three 
months of 1990 while boosting them in others a real estate trade 
group reported tuesday 
overall the national association of realtors said sales slipped 
16 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 381 million 
units during the januarymarch period down from 387 million units 
during the fourth quarter sales totaled 390 million during the 
first quarter of 1989 
association president norman d flynn said rising mortgage rates 
had the dual effect of spurring sales in moderatelypriced areas 
while curbing them in higherend markets 
buyers in affordable markets decided to buy before rates rose 
further while those in highcost areas held back flynn 
explained 
the trade groups survey showed the median price of existing 
homes rose 52 percent to 95900 up from 91200 during the same 
period of 1989 the median price means half of the homes cost more 
half less 
mortgage rates also rose starting the quarter at 983 percent 
and ending it at 1022 percent according to the federal home loan 
mortgage association rates have continued to rise and hit 1067 
percent at the end of last week 
nevertheless the realtors said resales are expected to remain 
stable during the year as economic conditions improve 
the realtors survey covered sales of existing singlefamily 
detached homes town houses apartment condominiums and 
cooperatives 
sales were up in 29 states ranging from a 491 percent jump in 
south dakota to a 09 percent increase in nevada at the same time 
vermont posted a 248 percent decrease the largest decline in the 
nation 
by region the west saw sales rise 3 percent to an annual rate 
of 680000 units dominated by activity in california flynn 
reported some softening in highcost coastal areas while sales in 
some lowerpriced interior areas increased 
the south had acrosstheboard increases up 07 percent to 146 
million units as many oilpatch areas continued to regain strength 
but the sales pace in the northeast continued to decline 
dropping 55 percent to 690000 units 
last quarters activity in the northeast reflected high home 
prices and rising interest rates according to john a tuccillo 
the realtor groups chief economist 
sales in the midwest dropped 49 percent to 980000 units due 
to increased interest rates and poor weather conditions the 
realtors said 
median prices rose sharpest in the west up 76 percent to 
143700 costs in the midwest rose 69 percent to 74200 
