postal service finances have perked up a bit 
but an official said tuesday that a loss of up to 15 billion is 
likely by the end of the fiscal year 
the us postal service said it had net income of 370 million 
in the first half of fiscal 1990 which began sept 1 
thats 289 million better than had been expected for the period 
postmaster general anthony frank told the agencys board of 
governors that an increase in the productivity of postal workers 
and lower than expected transportation costs led to the savings 
mail volume also increased slightly bringing in more money 
senior assistant postmaster general comer s coppie said a 
costofliving increase for postal workers was due this month and 
that other costs were rising 
overall coppie said the agency is likely to finish the fiscal 
year with a loss of between 13 billion and 15 billion 
the postal service already has filed for a rate increase 
including a boost to 30 cents for firstclass stamps if approved 
thats likely to take effect early next year 
