<TEXT>
the share of firsttime mothers receiving paid 
maternity leave has nearly tripled in recent years while only half 
as many have quit their jobs the census bureau said tuesday 
more than 60 percent of new mothers quit working from 1961 
through 1965 while only 28 percent did so from 1981 through 1985 
on the other hand almost half received paid maternity leave in 
the second survey period up from 16 percent in the first 
while the study work and family patterns of american women 
includes data only through 1985 it does show historical trends 
starting in the 1960s 
the report was released as congress is considering a bill that 
would require employers with 50 or more workers to offer unpaid 
time off with job and benefit protection for the care of newborn 
newly adopted or seriously ill children as well as to deal with 
personal health problems or ill spouses or parents 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said president bush urges 
companies to provide paid parental leaves voluntarily but is 
unwilling to force them to do it 
the report comes just a day after the national center for health 
statistics reported that the increase in births in recent years 
continued into 1989 with 4021000 births up from 3913000 a year 
earlier 
births have risen steadily in recent years as the giant baby 
boom generation passed through its prime childbearing years 
although this has resulted in an increase in the actual number 
of births birth rates remain well below those of the baby boom era 
of the 1950s and early 1960s 
the census report found that younger women are more likely to 
quit their jobs or to be fired when they become pregnant than are 
older mothers 
from the ages of 18 to 22 43 percent of new mothers left work 
while only 20 percent of those having a first child at age 25 and 
over left their jobs 
overall 63 percent of women having their first children from 
1961 to 1965 did not return to work the study said that fell to 
51 percent in the 197175 period and 28 percent from 1981 through 
1985 
those receiving paid maternity or sick leave when having their 
first baby totaled only 16 percent in the early 1960s by the first 
half of the 1970s it was 23 percent and in the first half of the 
1980s 47 percent 
the share of women receiving unpaid leave meaning they were 
promised a job on their return from maternity leave rose from 14 
percent in the early 1060s to 21 percent in the 1970s then slipped 
to 20 percent in the 1980s 
the share fired from their jobs was nearly constant 50 percent 
in the early 1960s and 46 percent in the later periods 
in the early 1960s 27 percent of firsttime mothers said they 
never stopped working that dipped to 17 percent in the early 
1970s but rose to 28 percent in the early 1980s 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

