milk production dropped last year but higher 
prices boosted sales receipts of dairy farmers to a record level 
the agriculture department said tuesday 
overall milk output in 1989 declined 1 percent to about 1443 
billion pounds from a record of 1452 billion pounds in 1988 the 
report said but cash receipts from milk sales rose 10 percent to 
194 billion eclipsing the old record of 185 billion set in 
1983 
milk production has been rising this year in response to higher 
prices and may edge up by 1 percent to 3 percent in 1990 possibly 
to another record level according to usda forecasters 
the annual report showed that actual marketings of milk in 1989 
totaled about 1421 billion pounds down from 1429 billion in 
1988 about 21 billion pounds were used on farms where produced 
including milk fed to calves and used by dairy producer families 
about 1411 billion pounds of the milk marketed was sold to 
plants and dealers for more than 191 billion an average of 
1356 per 100 pounds the report said 
more than 497 million quarts about two pounds each were sold 
directly to consumers for an average of 539 cents per quart those 
receipts totaled 2679 million 
the average number of milk cows in 1989 was reported at 
10127000 head down from 10262000 the year before but average 
milk production rose to 14244 pounds per cow last year from 14145 
in 1988 
