<TEXT>
the bush administration can modernize the air 
traffic control system without raising ticket taxes to pay for it 
the congressional audit agency said tuesday 
increased modernization costs and expanded use of the 
aviation trust fund to pay for operations expenses do not 
necessarily require an immediate increase in user fees john w 
hill jr of the general accounting office told a house panel 
the bush administration has proposed raising ticket taxes from 8 
percent to 10 percent to finance the modernization 
the administration has also proposed that the aviation trust 
fund pay a greater share of the operating costs of the federal 
aviation administration 
the trust fund was set up in 1970 to pay for the equipment costs 
of maintaining safety in the skies the fund is financed chiefly 
through ticket taxes but also through fees on cargo and aviation 
fuel 
despite its name it is a bookkeeping account which must be 
spent according to annual congressional directives 
hill testified before the public works and transportation 
investigations subcommittee the subcommittee is trying to 
determine if excess balances are building up and if so why congress 
is not spending them 
since 1971 the aviation trust fund account has been used for a 
share of faa personnel and administrative costs the administration 
has proposed raising the share from the current 58 percent to 85 
percent arguing that private commercial and general aviation 
account for 85 percent of the faas costs 
hill said the faa could afford to use the trust fund to cover 75 
percent of operating costs plus pay for modernization with no 
increase in fees 
hill referred to the national airspace system plan which was 
initiated in 1981 to replace computer radar and communication 
equipment major delays and addons have caused the estimated cost 
to rise from 12 billion to 16 billion 
faa now acknowledges that modernization will need continuous 
funding and not end in 1991 as its preliminary costbenefit 
analysis for the nas plan indicated hill said 
by being used to purchase government bonds that are not counted 
in the deficit the aviation and highway trust funds just mask the 
true size of the deficit instead of being spent to clear congested 
airways and repair highways critics say 
critics also say other similar trust funds elsewhere in the 
government are similarly used 
the transportation department projects a cash balance for the 
aviation fund of close to 15 billion by the end of september it 
was expected to take in 51 billion during the current fiscal 
year about twothirds of which is revenue from the ticket tax and 
a quarter is interest earnings but pay out only 35 billion 
similarly the department projects a cash balance of 18 billion 
in the highway fund by the end of september this year of which 7 
billion is in a mass transportation account 
hill said a real surplus of 34 billion will exist for new 
highway spending when the fiveyear spending authority for the 
highway fund ends in 1991 the highway fund is financed through a 
9centagallon gasoline tax and 15centagallon diesel tax was 
well as other fees 
the highway money goes to states which administer projects 
hill said states can afford much more highway spending than 
congress now allows with its spending ceilings 
he pointed out that in 1989 congress set a ceiling of 12 
billion even though 22 billion was available 
kate l moore assistant transportation secretary for budget and 
programs said the highway fund is highly leveraged with the 11 
billion balance supporting 33 in spending commitments through the 
addition of state funds 
she said much of the balance in the funds represents accumulated 
interest owed by the treasury since the surplus is invested in 
government securities spending down too much money would add to 
the deficit she said 
