<TEXT>
a soviet admiral urged president mikhail s 
gorbachev on tuesday to invoke strict law and order against 
draft evasion desertion and baltic insults against world war ii 
veterans 
the remarks by adm vasily grishanov at a rally in the bolshoi 
theater marking the defeat of nazi germany in 1945 drew prolonged 
applause from a crowd of veterans many of them decorated generals 
and admirals from the second world war 
gorbachev addressing the same meeting on the eve of a victory 
day military parade in red square received tepid applause for a 
speech that lauded veterans but dwelt largely on disarmament and 
josef stalins purge of the officer corps on the eve of world war 
ii 
grishanov a little known threestar admiral did not directly 
criticize gorbachev or the baltic republics of latvia lithuania 
and estonia for seeking to secede from the soviet union the first 
of the 15 soviet republics to take such a step 
but his speech was one of the clearest public expressions yet of 
dissatisfaction among officers of kremlin tolerance toward the 
separatist movements in the baltic republics 
the heart aches grishanov said unfortunately in recent 
years certain political forces have been persistently forming a 
negative attitude toward the soviet armed forces they are trying 
to break down the notion of the motherland for the young people 
as a result there is a phenomenon of pacifism evasion of 
military service and unfortunately even acts of desertion he 
said 
we veterans are calling upon the young men to be real men 
prepare to fulfill your constitutional duty of defending the 
motherland he said 
the whole society must take real care of its defenders in 
general there must be a strict civil law and order in the state 
he said 
the veterans nodded their heads repeatedly during the speech 
and burst into spontaneous applause at the mention of law and order 
the admiral appeared to be in his 70s but was not introduced 
as retired as is customary for officers no longer on active 
duty 
the way they treat war veterans in the baltic republics is a 
tragedy grishanov said alluding to assertions by baltic 
residents that the soviet soldiers occupied rather than liberated 
their nations during world war ii 
the soviet union forcibly annexed lithuania latvia and estonia 
in 1940 as part of a pact with nazi germany the soviet congress of 
peoples deputies in moscow passed a resolution saying that the 
nazisoviet pact was invalid but maintains that the annexation was 
voluntary 
many russians particularly in the military have been critical 
of gorbachev for allowing what they view as the dissolution of the 
soviet union and its alliance in eastern europe much of which was 
consolidated under arms during world war ii and its aftermath 
gorbachev reiterated his view that the reunification of germany 
would be welcome as long as the security of the soviet union and 
other countries was ensured he warned that any effort to change 
postwar borders would be a great fatal mistake 
the soviet union along with wartime allies the united states 
britain and france is now meeting with representatives of the two 
german states to try to work out the formula for reunification a 
major sticking point is the wests demand that a united germany be 
a part of nato 
gorbachev rejects that demand but did not directly address the 
issue in his speech 
he sharply criticized stalins repression of the soviet officer 
corps in the late 1930s and the dictators unwillingness to 
believe that germany was planning an attack 
gorbachev credited stalin with managing the system that turned 
the soviet unions war fortunes around but he said the system only 
worked because during a war stalin had to leave many decisions to 
the intelligence and initiative of subordinates in the field rather 
than managing the war from the capital 
he sat quietly through grishanovs speech twiddling his fingers 
on the green baizecovered table in front of him as he often does 
when listening to speeches critical of his policies 
soviet authorities were planning a military parade in red square 
on wednesday to mark the 45th anniversary of the end of world war 
ii in europe 
