<TEXT>
six alleged violations of federal mine 
ventilation rules contributed to a methane explosion that killed 10 
kentucky miners last year the government said tuesday 
a federal investigation into the blast found that some pyro 
mining co managers knew that explosive methane gas was 
accumulating in the mine four days before the explosion but they 
did not maintain required records that would have alerted others 
a report by the labor departments mine safety and health 
administration also said that autopsies found traces of marijuana 
in one victim and marijuana and cocaine in another but there was 
no evidence that linked the drug use to the sept 13 explosion in 
wheatcroft ky 
james greenlee executive vice president of costain coal inc 
which owns pyro said the company had not reviewed the report and 
would not discuss its findings yet 
the company allowed six violations of federal ventilation 
requirements to occur in the days and hours before the accident 
said william tattersall assistant labor secretary for mine safety 
and health 
the combination of violations set the stage for the 
explosion tattersall said 
the mine safety and health agency does not immediately propose 
fines against companies for allegedly violating safety regulations 
but eventually the company could face up to 100000 in fines an 
agency official said 
the report alleged that managers failed to make required checks 
for the deadly gas in the hours before the explosion failed to 
keep enough clean air in the mine to sweep out methane and made a 
series of changes in air pathways that caused a methane buildup the 
day of the disaster 
the report said mining equipment that did not meet federal 
requirements was operated in the mine 
federal investigators were unable to determine exactly what 
triggered the explosion although they identified five 
possibilities a cutting torch a sccop tractor with multiple 
electrical safety deficiencies detonation of a blasting cap a 
spark generated by falling roof rock or snapping of a steel wire 
under tension 
