<TEXT>
defense secretary dick cheney said 
tuesday he wants nato to maintain the policy that allows for a 
firststrike use of nuclear weapons in the event of a warsaw pact 
invasion of europe 
cheney en route to a nato session reviewing nuclear strategy 
told reporters that the alliances defense ministers will lay the 
groundwork for a lengthy review of nato strategy involving the use 
of conventional and nuclear systems 
president bush called for the review last thursday in light of 
the political and military changes that have swept europe the past 
year 
the presidents request came as he announced he had scrapped 
plans to replace shortrange nuclear missiles in europe with an 
updated version and put aside plans as well to upgrade the nuclear 
artillery shells in natos arsenal 
cheney was to be joined by the defense ministers of 14 other 
nato nations for the first of four sessions leading up to a summit 
in london in july of all nato leaders 
cheney said he intended to brief the allies on bushs 
initiative which comes as the member nations reassess natos 
political and military significance amid the crumbling of its 
longtime foe the warsaw pact 
bushs decision on shortrange weapons does not signal the 
beginning of the removal of us nuclear weapons from europe 
cheney stressed 
that does not mean that you want to walk away from the role of 
nuclear weapons in the overall defense of europe cheney said 
we think us nuclear capability both theater and strategic 
will continue to be an important part of our overall alliance 
strategy 
cheney said the flexible response doctrine allowing for the 
first use of nuclear weapons has provided security for the 
alliance for decades and im not eager to remove one part of it 
i would not give that up he said at another point 
cheney was asked whether the debate will now switch from the 
hotly contested issue of the lance missile to alliance plans to 
modernize airlaunched nuclear missiles known as tasms tactical 
air to surface missile the secretary said he didnt see any 
reason for the defense ministers to discuss the issue 
theres nothing thats happened within the last few weeks that 
in any way changes our approach to tasm cheney said 
nato secretary general manfred woerner who accompanied cheney 
on the flight said monday he expected the defense ministers to 
formally issue a statement supporting bushs initiative on 
shortrange weapons 
he said he also expected them to direct the supreme allied 
commander in europe us gen john galvin to undertake a 
comprehensive study of the alliance need for its nuclear weaponry 
cheney said he expected the meeting scheduled for wednesday and 
thursday to focus on both conventional and nuclear forces and 
where we will go with respect to arms control 
the meeting is with members of the nuclear planning group which 
is composed of the defense ministers of the 16 nato nations except 
france and iceland 
the secretary said it was a reasonable guess that the nato 
review process may last into next year given ongoing eastwest 
talks on reducing conventional forces but that he wouldnt put a 
timetable on the study 
