<TEXT>
the senate voted tuesday to allow law 
enforcement intelligence and tax agents to spend their off time 
soliciting campaign contributions from colleagues and taking other 
active roles in partisan politics 
on a 5146 vote senate democrats rejected a republican attempt 
to exclude employees of the fbi the cia the internal revenue 
service the justice department and the federal election commission 
from a proposal to relax rules on political activities by 
government workers 
the fbi cia and justice department are still in a special 
category said senate republican leader bob dole of kansas i 
do not believe we want to politicize those agencies 
democrats denied trying to politicize those workers or any of 
29 million civil service and postal employees they claim would 
benefit from their proposed relaxation of the hatch act 
sen john glenn dohio said his bill overhauling the 
51yearold law was intended to clarify conflicting rulings on what 
political activities federal workers can participate in while 
totally forbidding such activities on the job 
the hatch act now forbids the nations 3 million federal civil 
service and postal workers from participating actively in politics 
off the job but allows them to wear campaign buttons while at work 
glenns bill would outlaw the buttons but lift most restrictions 
on offthejob activities so that federal employees could hold 
party offices and solicit campaign funds from their coworkers but 
not from the general public 
doles amendment to maintain the prohibitions on campaign 
activities by irs fbi cia and fec workers and career federal 
prosecutors was one of several unsuccessful gop attempts tuesday to 
chip away at glenns bill 
laws restricting those people and what they can do are already 
on the books glenn said they cannot use information gained on 
the job politically 
also defeated were gop amendments to maintain a ban on federal 
workers holding office in the two political parties and delaying 
any changes in the hatch law until after a campaign finance reform 
bill is enacted 
the first amendment by sen william v roth rnh was 
defeated on a 6432 vote and the second by gop whip alan k 
simpson of wyoming was rejected 6136 
republicans have contended the entire bill amounts to a pot of 
gold for the democratic party because unionized public employees 
and their political action committees overwhelmingly favor 
democrats 
lf we banned all pacs there wouldnt be much demand for this 
bill said dole holding open a threat that republicans later 
this week might try to attach to the measure their proposed package 
of campaign finance reforms 
the only purpose of this bill is to make the federal employee 
union pacs fatter of which 88 percent of their campaign 
donations goes to the other party he said 
despite repeated assertions that president bush will veto any 
changes in the hatch law democrats so far have garnered several 
votes from republicans on each challenge by the gop leadership to 
the bill 
the house approved a much broader revision of the hatch act by 
an overwhelming 29790 vote more than a year ago 
