president fw de klerk left 
tuesday on a major european tour aimed at convincing western 
leaders that south africa has changed enough to justify an end to 
international efforts to isolate it 
it is wonderful to go to europe with the knowledge that south 
africa is busy taking its rightful place in the international 
community the south african leader said at an airport news 
conference before his departure 
the first stop on the ninecountry 18day tour is france where 
president francois mitterrand has shunned previous south african 
leaders in protest against the system of white minority rule 
although apartheid still exists de klerks historic talks last 
week to settle differences with the african national congress have 
led the french leader and others to agree to give de klerk a 
hearing 
in recent months de klerk also freed political prisoners 
including african national congress leader nelson mandela and had 
taken other steps toward reform 
the evening news on south africas governmentrun television 
said a senior government source described the tour as a concerted 
effort to pull south africa from the morass the country has found 
itself in 
the visit is not only going to be demanding of the state 
president but also of the utmost importance to south africa the 
television said 
after france de klerk will visit belgium italy west germany 
britain spain switzerland greece and portugal his exact 
itinerary is being kept secret for security reasons but he is to 
meet the heads of government in every country 
among his hosts will be british prime minister margaret 
thatcher king juan carlos of spain and west german chancellor 
helmut kohl 
i welcome the opportunity for reevaluating what is happening 
in south africa to the heads of state and heads of government i 
will be visiting de klerk said at his news conference 
many western countries have imposed economic and trading 
sanctions against south africa and cut athletic entertainment and 
scientific exchanges because of apartheid under which the black 
majority of 28 million in this nation of 37 million residents has 
no vote in national affairs 
but de klerk has pledged to end white rule and share power with 
the black majority in the governments firstever talks with the 
african national congress the countrys most powerful black 
political organization the two sides agreed to work together to 
end political violence and clear the way for formal negotiations on 
a new constitution 
two months ago mandela had been calling for increased sanctions 
and complete diplomatic isolation of south africa but after last 
weeks talks he said the anc would not seek new sanctions 
government television reported that spain is considering ending 
its entertainment and sports boycott of south africa in response to 
de klerks visit and the talks with the anc 
the south african foreign ministry described it as the most 
extensive foreign trip by any south african head of government 
since the ruling national party came to power in 1948 
there will be no slipping in by the back door government 
television assured viewers in the past south african leaders have 
visited foreign countries as tourists 
