<TEXT>
the house approved legislation tuesday to put 
into effect a 1972 treaty against biological weapons 
by a vote of 4080 the house approved a bill which makes it 
illegal to develop and possess biological weapons the bill goes to 
the white house where president bush is expected to sign it into 
law 
under the legislation any individual corporation or government 
is prohibited from developing or possessing any biological weapons 
and prohibited from assisting a foreign state or organization from 
doing so 
biological weapons are harmful forms of bacteria viruses fungi 
or naturally occuring toxins that could be directed at an enemy a 
biological weapon could be unleashed on an unsuspecting public by 
using it in a liquid to contaminate water or in an aerosol that is 
dropped by bomb 
in 1925 the geneva protocol banned the first use in war of 
biological and chemical weapons but did not address the 
development production possession or transfer of the weapons 
fortyfour years later president nixon ordered the defense 
department to destory its arsenal of biological weapons the united 
states then spearheaded the fight for an international ban on 
production and possession of them 
on april 10 1972 in washington moscow and london 111 
countries signed the biological weapons convention which prohibits 
production and possession of the weapons 
the senate ratified the treaty two years later 
according to the pact each nation must take any necessary 
measures to prohibit biological weapons at home legislation was 
introduced in congress over the years to include the prohibition in 
us law but the measures never got far largely because no 
administration or powerful congressional group pushed for passage 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

