a lawyer for three droughtplagued western 
states asked a federal judge tuesday to order the us army corps 
of engineers to maintain water levels in a crucial reservoir along 
the missouri river 
but lawyers for the corps which wants to lower the rivers 
reservoirs to support shipping downstream contended a federal 
judge has no authority to dictate how the corps should manage its 
system of six missouri river dams 
former south dakota gov william janklow who is representing 
the three states said lowering the level of lake oahe would 
destroy this years hatch of millions of walleye eggs that would 
deal a 20 million blow to north dakota and south dakotas tourism 
industries he said 
both north dakota and south dakota rely on fishing and attendant 
tourism to boost their economies janklow told us district judge 
patrick conmy 
we dont live in wealthy states we have very limited 
economic opportunities available to us he said 
south dakota north dakota and montana are suing the corps in an 
effort to block the agencys plans to allow the water level of lake 
oahe to fall 3 feet before june 1 the lake stretches from 
southcentral north dakota into south dakota 
the three states are seeking a preliminary injunction to force 
the corps to maintain the lake at its current depth until june 1 
on tuesday the lake was measured at 15884 feet above sea level 
the judge said he would rule by noon wednesday on the request 
the lawsuit was filed friday and tuesday was the only day of 
arguments 
but charles findlay a justice department attorney representing 
the corps said conmy had no authority to intervene in the agencys 
management of the river reservoirs 
a judge may step in only if the corps acted in bad faith and 
the agency has consulted the affected states extensively in making 
its management decisions findlay said 
the three states request would block shipping in the missouris 
navigation channel which stretches from sioux city iowa to st 
louis findlay argued 
keeping the rivers level low also could disrupt the nesting of 
two federally protected rare birds the piping plover and interior 
least tern he said 
janklow countered that the birds would not be affected and any 
harm to the shipping industry was exaggerated 
shipping contributes only 14 million in benefits to the system 
compared to 67 million in benefits from fishing and recreation 
janklow said 
