<TEXT>
there wasnt much doubt that kevin kline could 
play hamlet 
he did it four years ago at the new york shakespeare festival in 
an odd uneven production directed by liviu ciulei its biggest 
plus was kline who offered a thoughtful clearspoken but 
lowkeyed portrait of the danish prince 
now hamlet and kline are together again for a second time as 
part of the festivals sixyear marathon of all of shakespeares 
plays in addition to playing the title character kline now has 
taken on the task of directing the play himself 
kline the director may not yet be the equal of kline the actor 
but he has done a respectable job this is a nononsense cleanly 
performed hamlet done with a minimum of production clutter in 
this version the text is all and no one speaks it better than 
kline 
kline the actor has improved since his last outing hes more 
relaxed freer and a little looser with the plays tragedy and 
moments of comedy than he was in 1986 yet he doesnt neglect the 
poetry that is such an important part of the role 
this hamlet has more passion than klines previous incarnation 
he grieves openly for his dead father his outrage at his mothers 
marriage to his uncle is fiercer his relentless humiliation of 
ophelia is more unnerving almost sadistic his wit and bitter 
sense of humor is more sharply defined particularly in the 
gravediggers scene when he ruminates on the nature of life and 
death and his realization of what he must do to avenge his 
fathers death is more carefully plotted out it builds 
appropriately to a bloody climax that seems inevitable from what 
has gone before 
kline has staged the play simply with few props and the barest 
of stage sets just a burgundy curtain hanging on a back wall the 
costumes are modern dress when hamlet first appears wearing a 
buttonedup white shirt with a high collar and a black suit he 
looks like a refugee from one of new yorks downtown rock clubs 
claudius done up in red sash and a blue military uniform 
resembles an admiral in dry dock and gertrude wears a ballgown 
that would be just as appropriate at the plaza as at elsinore 
there are a few awkward touches the playwithinaplay is oddly 
staged with claudius and gertrude on the platform with the actors 
who are reenacting claudius crime and the duel at the end of the 
evening seems cramped on the anspacher theaters small playing 
area the fight almost careens into the audience 
for the most part the play has been cast with remarkable care 
brian murray is an unctuous claudius who nevertheless manages to 
generate some sympathy for his nasty predictament 
dana ivey in the plays most thankless role is a regal 
unyielding gertrude while diane venora is a vulnerable ophelia 
able to make the characters famous mad scene shattering rather 
than silly best of all is joseph sommers polonius priggish 
without being petulant and whose death can be seen as a loss even 
by hamlet 
kline is a generous actordirector allowing each performer 
down to the smallest role a chance to shine but what makes this 
an enriching hamlet is klines fidelity to the play itself as 
an actor and now as a director 
</TEXT>
