antisemitism is rising in the soviet union in 
the age of glasnost according to two surveys released to congress 
on tuesday 
in one survey 77 percent of the people polled in moscow said 
they thought most of their countrymen were antijewish and 60 
percent believed some soviets harbored such feelings 
the survey released by the american jewish committee found 48 
percent of the respondents believe antijewish sentiment is 
increasing in the soviet union while 44 percent said such feelings 
were unchanged five percent said antisemitism was declining 
the poll of 506 randomly chosen moscow adults found 91 percent 
of the respondents thought jews should be alllowed to decide for 
themselves whether to emigrate 
the american jewish committee along with the national science 
foundation the university of houston and the soviet academy of 
sciences paid for the poll 
the likely uncertainty in a sample of 506 people would be more 
than four percentage points either way according to a standard 
statistical calculation 
another survey conducted by the jewish research center of the 
soviet sociological association in moscow focused on about 500 
soviet jewish leaders 
about 73 percent said they had experienced or witnessed an act 
of antisemitism in the last six months of 1989 
the polls were released at a hearing of the congressional human 
rights caucus 
richard schifter the assistant secretary of state said 
official antisemitism has declined since soviet president mikhail 
s gorbachev instituted reforms in 1986 
at the same time liberalization inside the soviet union has 
allowed groups pressing the antisemitic case to become more 
visible 
the number of jews leaving the soviet union has increased 
dramatically with thousands leaving the country each month in 
1989 71000 jews emigrated up from 914 in 1986 
