<TEXT>
the labor department issued a report friday that 
created quite a shock hardly anybody concerned with the future of 
the economy failed to react to it within minutes 
many economists were unnerved after reading the report they 
wondered what had gone wrong with their interpretation of the data 
and why they had not foreseen what occurred 
some viewed the new report as indicative of an economy even 
weaker than realized some saw it as a sign the bottom had been 
reached and that the economy would begin strengthening the stock 
market suddenly came alive 
whatever they made of the numbers hardly an economist who wants 
to remain in the public eye failed to offer an explanation 
interpretation or forecast 
most significant of all the reactions was the widespread view 
it seemed to sweep through the investment community in minutes 
that the numbers would force the federal reserve to reconsider 
lifting interest rates 
what caused this commotion 
the april jobless rate and numbers that created it thats what 
what did the rate do it rose to 54 percent in april from 52 
percent in march or if you include military to 53 percent from 
51 percent 
you might wonder how little numbers like that can cause big 
reactions like those that occurred and your wonderment is 
justified after a weekend of reflection you may be sure that many 
people are less excited than before 
that short period of reflection for example might have caused 
some of them to realize that the change in the numbers might be a 
matter of methodology rather than reality and that the numbers 
might yet be revised 
revisions are common and they include the march numbers after 
studying their data for example labor department analysts raised 
by 103000 their estimate of payroll increases in that month the 
earlier figure was 26000 
a single months data has always been suspect simply because it 
could be an isolated event that event could be a real one an 
actual occurrence but it also could be due to faulty counting or 
to seasonal adjusting 
while realizing this the economic fraternity nevertheless 
reacted as if to a major event and one conceivable explanation 
might be boredom a look at the statistics over the past year or so 
provides the basis for that theory 
since last april that is the most inclusive monthly 
unemployment rate one that includes military has varied from 53 
percent only once that was last may when it dipped to 52 percent 
of the labor force 
in short the jobless rate has provided little if any clue to 
the economys direction in that time a time in which the economic 
fraternity was looking far wide and everywhere for any little 
indication of direction 
placed in that perspective therefore the april jobless rate 
represented a big change and to be sure some other elements in 
the report were significant such as a continued decline of 
manufacturing employment 
but even janet norwood commissioner of labor statistics 
thought the report wasnt really of major significance and she so 
informed congress she told them that 
thus far we can discern no meaningful changes in the 
measures that might signal a deteriorating unemployment situation 
in particular mrs norwood said neither the number of newly 
unemployed those jobless less than than five weeks nor the 
number of job losers has started to climb 
