<TEXT>
greyhound lines inc has resumed most of its 
operations but some analysts question whether the company has 
enough cash to avoid bankruptcy as it tries to recover from a 
9week walkout by bus drivers 
chairman fred g currey said monday the strike was in effect 
concluded from the point of view of daytoday operations he 
said greyhound is serving areas which brought in 98 percent of its 
revenue last year and will be running at 90 percent of scheduled 
prestrike miles by june 19 
union officials challenged the claim pointing to the companys 
recent announcement of a 558 million firstquarter loss they 
said curry was trying to scare striking drivers back to work 
in addition to the loss greyhound has said it would not make a 
975 million interest payment due may 15 the company also did not 
pay about 5 million in lease payments due at the end of april 
some analysts have questioned whether the dallasbased company 
will be able to pay bills to operate even if creditors dont call 
in their loans and force the company into bankruptcy a 
possibility because of the missed payments 
greyhound had amassed a strike fund of more than 50 million but 
has said the frequently violent walkout in which some buses have 
been hit by gunfire has cost more than anticipated 
in documents filed with the securities and exchange commission 
last week greyhound said it had spent 20 million on beefed up 
security legal fees and extra driver training 
im surprised at how much cash theyre burning said leigh 
walzer an analyst with rd smith amp co in new york cash could 
become a real bind walzer gave the company only a 20 percent 
chance of surviving the strike without having to file for chapter 
11 bankruptcy protection from creditors 
currey would not disclose greyhounds cash resources in an 
interview monday but he said money that would have been used to 
cover interest and lease costs is being used to help operate the 
company 
nevertheless currey said creditors recognize greyhound can be 
rebuilt and we expect and weve received cooperation 
currey said ridership increased last week to its highest levels 
since the strike began although it remains between 65 percent and 
75 percent of yearago levels 
revenue is running at about the same level he said and remains 
less than expenses although the carrier is near breakeven 
he suggested revenues would be 85 percent to 90 percent of last 
years levels by mid to late summer curry also said the company 
could post a profit by next year 
union officials have challenged the companys claims of restored 
service and said curreys victory cry was a publicity stunt 
its a common ploy to try to scare a few more strikers into 
scabbing by announcing that theres no hope said aflcio 
spokesman rex hardesty 
mr curreys claim that the greyhound strike is over is like 
napoleon claiming victory at waterloo its both ridiculous and 
false said jim la sala international president of the 
amalgamated transit union the umbrella organization for the 
amalgamated council of greyhound local unions 
the company proposed a contract offer saturday that would have 
eliminated 4500 union jobs changed from permile wage rates to 
hourly wage rates and imposed a fouryear wage freeze union 
officials called the proposal an insult and refused to put it 
to a vote no further talks were scheduled 
currey did not rule out resuming negotiations with the union 
noting it remains the licensed bargaining agent for the drivers he 
said the company would continue to need drivers as it expands 
the union which represents 6300 drivers and about 3000 office 
and maintenance workers walked off the job march 2 
as of monday the company said 548 union drivers had crossed 
picket lines it also had hired 2888 new drivers and had 501 
others in school which would give it 3937 available drivers by 
may 16 
greyhound has said before it could operate a full system with 
about 3200 drivers although more are needed for the busy summer 
travel season 
the company also said it would reduce its charter operation 
sharply from 197 cities to 19 cities and cut unprofitable miles 
company officials could not provide the number of destinations 
that will lose service but currey said local carriers already 
have moved on to many of those routes and greyhound is trying to 
locate new carriers for the others 
it would appear that the company needed this strike to justify 
abandoning bus service to rural communities across the country 
said the atus la sala 
