<TEXT>
the jurisdictional turf battle between the 
federal agencies regulating securities and futures markets moves to 
the senate panel that oversees one of the rivals the commodity 
futures trading commission 
the cftc has been locked in a war of words with the securities 
and exchange commission the stock market regulator over which 
should oversee financial products that have elements of both a 
security and a futures contract socalled hybrid products include 
stock index futures 
the senate agriculture committee was scheduled to hear this 
afternoon from top officials of the four agencies that make up the 
white house working group on financial markets the federal 
reserve board the sec cftc and the treasury department the group 
was set up in the wake of the 1987 stock market crash to handle 
intermarket issues 
fed chairman alan greenspan sec chairman richard breeden cftc 
chairman wendy gramm and treasury undersecretary robert glauber 
were scheduled to appear at the hearing 
the four already have aired their views before congressional 
panels and in numerous speeches and interviews breeden and glauber 
are on one side gramm on the other with greenspan somewhere in 
between 
breeden and glauber think at the very least the sec should be 
given control of stock index futures these products now 
controlled by the futures exchanges with cftc oversight allow 
investors to speculate on the stock market without buying the 
underlying stocks 
a federal appeals court last year ruled that such hybrid 
products come under the purview of the cftc if they have the 
slightest similarity to a futures contract 
breeden has complained that the court ruling discourages 
financial innovation and drives new products to foreign markets 
greenspan says he is slightly in favor of giving the sec 
control of stock index futures 
but he is against merging the sec and cftc which has been 
proposed in legislation introduced in the house last month 
greenspan also says one agency should be responsible for setting 
margin limits but he doesnt know which one margins are the down 
payments investors must make to buy securities or futures contracts 
on credit 
margins for the securities markets usually 50 percent of the 
total price are set by the fed margins for futures contracts are 
set by the exchanges with limited input by the cftc and typically 
are much lower 
critics claim that the disparity in margins limits leads to a 
trading strategy known as index arbitrage in which speculators 
trying to take advantage of brief price differences between the two 
markets move huge blocks of stock back and forth 
that say critics leads to wild price swings that frightens 
small investors from the stock market 
but gramm disagrees with those criticisms in a speech to a 
futures industry conference last week she said the attempt to grab 
cftc authority over stock index futures is driven by jealousy 
on wall street and regulatory imperialism at the sec 
in an informal session with reporters last friday breeden said 
his bid to acquire control of stock index futures was for the good 
of the economy 
this is a policy dispute he said this isnt a question 
of turf 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
