his departure effective wednesday automatically elevates 
nicholas j nicholas the president of time warner into the post 
of cochief executive with ross nicholas 50 is expected to 
become the sole chief executive on rosss retirement from that post 
in july 1994 
munro 59 joined the company in 1957 and became president and 
chief executive in 1980 he has been chairman and chief executive 
since sept 1 1986 sharing those posts with ross since time 
acquired a majority of warners stock last summer the buyout was 
completed earlier this year 
some time warner shareholders are unhappy that they were not 
allowed to vote on a 200 a share takeover offer from paramount 
communications inc that time spurned in favor of its 14 billion 
deal with warner 
times stock rose as high as 18275 a share during last 
summers threeway takeover fight but the stock of its successor 
company time warner closed monday at 9450 a share on the new 
york stock exchange 
munro ross and nicholas have argued that their plans to 
combine time and warner was a better deal for shareholders in the 
long run than paramounts 122 billion offer for time would have 
been 
the delaware chancery court backed them up ruling in favor of 
managements right to follow its own business judgment that a 
combination of time and warner was the better course despite what 
shareholders might have wanted 
that comes as little comfort to some shareholders and their 
advisors who note the companys stock is trading for less than half 
of what paramount offered and near its 52week low of 8750 a 
share 
why should shareholders risk their money in american companies 
when they are treated this way william steiner a time warner 
shareholder from great neck ny asked on the eve of the annual 
meeting 
institutional shareholder services inc a washington 
dcbased consulting firm that advises big shareholders 
recommended withholding votes for four former time inc directors 
up for election at todays meeting 
time management was faced here with a choice between a deal 
carefully crafted to protect its own managers and one that was not 
but offered a substantial premium to shareholders the consulting 
firm said 
the deal was completed earlier this year 
the combined company is a leader in magazines film production 
recorded music pay television services and cable tv systems 
operations 
despite a big debt load stemming from the merger time warner 
has launched a new weekly magazine entertainment weekly bought 
the west coast magazine and book concern lane publishing and 
acquired a 195 percent stake in the theme parks operator six flags 
corp it sold the textbook publisher scott foresman and co 
the company recently reported a 187 million loss in the first 
quarter compared with a loss of 217 million a year earlier the 
losses reflected the costs of the buyout of warner 
but it also noted that operating income for the quarter 
excluding interest taxes and costs of the merger was up 16 
percent at 536 million while revenue rose to 274 billion from 
255 billion 
