<TEXT>
fewer dollars may be involved but prosecutors 
say the trial of three futures traders concerns offenses no less 
serious than those committed by wall street felons ivan boesky and 
michael milken 
cheating is cheating said us attorney ira raphaelson 
jury selection began today in the us district court trial of 
robert d mosky danny l scheck and david zatz three traders of 
swiss franc futures on the chicago mercantile exchange they are 
accused of swindling customers 
they represent one of four groups of chicago futures traders 
47 in all who were indicted last year after an unprecedented 
sting fbi agents posing as corrupt traders secretly tape recorded 
conversations that the government contends reveal organized fraud 
among traders at the merc and the rival chicago board of trade the 
worlds two largest futures exchanges 
us district judge ann c williams decided monday and today to 
allow defense lawyers to introduce evidence of their clients 
lawful behavior to show that the difference between legal and 
illegal trading is unclear 
also stung by the investigation was a clerk who has pleaded 
guilty along with 15 of the traders to reduced charges in 
exchange for cooperation with prosecutors none has been sentenced 
prosecutors have not revealed how much money they believe was 
stolen by traders saying only that the alleged schemes involved 
hundreds of investors and thousands of trades 
the scandal dealt a black eye to the reputation of the futures 
markets which already were perceived as freewheeling in much the 
same way the insider trading cases of the 1980s tarnished the image 
of the stock market 
the chicago exchanges and their federal regulators responded 
with tougher antifraud measures and congress is considering 
proposals to strengthen the integrity of the markets 
new york commodities lawyer thomas russo said the scandal 
probably involves less money and public harm than the wall street 
insider trading cases in which boesky and milken paid fines and 
restitution totaling 700 million to settle criminal charges 
but russo said i think the amount of money is not the 
material issue in these cases it goes beyond dollars to the 
integrity of the markets 
mosky scheck and zatz are charged with multiple counts of mail 
or wire fraud and violations of the federal commodity exchange act 
each count carries up to five years in prison 
mosky also is charged with racketeering conspiracy for which he 
could be sent to prison for 20 years and be forced to forfeit 
personal assets including exchange membership 
in court documents the government has portrayed mosky as a 
ringleader who persuaded scheck and zatz to accept the 
responsibility and costs of trading errors he made while executing 
customer orders in the swiss franc trading pit 
the government contends mosky later repaid scheck and zatz by 
manipulating customer orders sometimes via trades conducted 
illegally outside the pit 
the governments evidence includes the fbi tapes mountains of 
trading records and the expected testimony of two other swiss franc 
traders each of whom pleaded guilty in august 
