supermarkets will have to offer more lowfat 
products environmentally conscious policies and onestop shopping 
conveniences like banking to compete in the 1990s industry leaders 
said tuesday 
the mom and pop grocery may be taking a step into the past 
at the food marketing institutes trade show which covers more 
than 1 million square feet of space and involves more than 1000 
companies chiefly food retailers 
topics of discussion include newage trends such as 
micromarketing to target individual tastes of shoppers and 
hiring more minorities to help erase an image of a whitemale 
dominated business 
the supermarket truly is the microcosm of the lifestyle of 
america and must reflect the changes in lifestyle to survive 
said timothy hammonds senior vice president of the food marketing 
institute 
the washingtonbased group whose 1600 members operate about 
19000 retail food stores nationwide said a survey of 1005 
shoppers found that fat content beat cholesterol and salt as the 
biggest nutrition concern for consumers 
the nationwide survey based on telephone interviews was 
conducted in january and released tuesday the third day of the 
fourday meeting 
two years ago cholesterol was the biggest concern hammonds said 
shoppers surveyed this year said they are buying more fruits and 
vegetables more chicken and fish and less meat and fatty 
products store managers are responding to these changes by 
stocking their shelves accordingly hammonds said 
an increasing number of supermarkets are addressing the nations 
solidwaste crisis by recycling said patrick collins president of 
ralphs grocery co a supermarket chain based in the los angeles 
area 
collins said 87 percent of wholesalers and retailers pick up 
recyclable waste products from their stores for consolidation at 
distribution centers 
another trend is onestop shopping which has turned the 
neighborhood grocery store into a selfcontained minimall offering 
services ranging from instore restaurants to banking 
all supermarkets will be doing that to meet the needs and 
time pressures of twoincome families hammonds said 
it doesnt mean the small store or convenience store is going 
to go away but theyll have to specialize to stay afloat he 
said 
as more women and minorities enter the work force supermarkets 
must make an effort to hire them and not just for entrylevel 
