<TEXT>
the son of a washington real estate magnate 
was accused tuesday of illegally passing confidential information 
about one of his fathers deals to a friend who allegedly traded on 
the inside information 
in a civil complaint filed at federal court in chicago the 
securities and exchange commission accused b francis saul iii of 
violating the insider trading act of 1984 the sec also charged 
sauls friend peter david garvy 
both men are 28 and chicago residents 
in 1988 the sec alleged saul son of b francis saul ii of 
chevy chase md told garvy a former school roomate about a 
proposed tender offer one his fathers companies westminster 
investing corp had made for another saul concern the bf saul 
real estate investment trust 
according to the complaint garvy bought 5500 shares in the 
investment trust before the tender offer was made public 
the complaint also charged that garvy told his father eugene 
70 of hinsdale ill and a friend betsy perk 29 of chicago 
about the pending deal and they purchased shares in the saul trust 
the complaint does not accuse the elder saul garvys father or 
ms perk of any wrongdoing 
this kid is totally innocent hes taken a lie detector test 
and passed it 100 percent said sauls attorney george rogers 
we intend to fight it immediately as soon as we can get to trial 
and we expect to win 
rogers said he was surprised the sec was bringing the case 
despite a federal appeals court decision in new york last week that 
overturned an insider trading case in which a broker received 
merger information from a client whose family owned the company in 
question 
sometimes people have to be told twice no ones ever accused 
the government of being smart said robert stephenson garvys 
attorney in chicago adding that his client also denied the charges 
and would seek a quick trial 
the sec charged that garvy his father and ms perk made a total 
of 61000 in profits using the information supplied by the younger 
saul 
the sec is seeking from both garvy and the younger saul who was 
not accused of trading for himself a total of three times the 
total illegal profits or 183000 in penalties 
</TEXT>
