<DOCNO> AP900508-0276 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
international monetary fund officials approved 
a record 60 billion increase in resources tuesday to meet growing 
demands for assistance from emerging democracies in eastern europe 
and debtstrapped nations in latin america 
the authorization from the imfs policysetting interim 
committee came after the panel adopted a usbacked proposal to 
crack down on countries that are delinquent in repaying their imf 
loans 
the 50 percent increase which still must be approved by the 
voting membership of the 152nation fund would boost imf lending 
resources to 180 billion 
third world countries had fought to double imf resources 
contending 240 billion is needed to ensure that economic 
assistance to eastern europe does not crowd out support for latin 
america and africa 
btg chidzero finance minister for zimbabwe said greater 
support from the imf and its sister lending organization the world 
bank was critical to avert falling into a crisis of 
international development finance in the present decade 
on another matter the finance officials stopped short of 
endorsing a proposal to create an environmental fund in the world 
bank to supply 13 billion in lowinterest loans over three years 
the money would be used to address crossborder environmental 
problems such as global warming the growth of deserts river 
system pollution and destruction of the ozone layer 
france is backing the new fund but the united states and 
several other countries are opposed 
treasury secretary nicholas f brady in remarks prepared for 
tuesdays closeddoor sessions of the development committee called 
the environmental issue of great importance to the united 
states but he said approval of the new fund should be delayed 
until questions concerning current world bank environmental 
programs were addressed 
in a statement the development committee said that it had 
agreed that further work was necessary on the proposal and that 
in the meantime the world bank should take steps to reinforce its 
existing environmental programs 
french finance minister pierre beregovoy had pleaded with other 
countries to approve the program now and warned time is 
passing 
bargaining over the increase in imf resources at times became 
intense according to participants in the meetings arguing for the 
us position brady noted the administration must win suport for 
the proposal from a democraticcontrolled congress 
canadian finance minister michael wilson head of the interim 
committee said that to get the final agreement each country had 
to put a little water in its wine and accept compromises 
the united states which had wanted to delay the next round of 
funding negotiations until 1995 agreed to a 1993 date in return 
the united states achieved a key demand for tougher procedures for 
poor countries that owe 4 billion in back payments to the imf 
delinquent countries who adopt economic reforms would be 
eligible for money from a special imf fund however nations behind 
in their payments could lose their voting rights also the agency 
could sell gold roughly equivalent to the members original 
contributions to meet the obligations of defaulting debtors 
the 11 nations behind in their payments are the sudan zambia 
peru costa rica honduras guyana somalia sierra leone 
cambodia vietnam and panama 
the imf increase was also tied up with a diplomatic question of 
the rankings of the biggest economic powers in the fund the 
rankings govern how much voting power the nations have 
americas no 1 ranking and voting strength was left unchanged 
at 19 percent however japan vaulted from no 5 to no 2 tied 
with west germany britain previously ranked no 2 dropped into a 
tie for fourth place with france 
on another matter polish finance minister leszek balcerowicz 
told reporters he had held discussions during the twoday meetings 
on polands efforts to reduce its 41 billion foreign debt 
balcerowicz reported progress in negotiations with commercial 
banks using debtreduction guidelines called for by brady but he 
indicated less success in the effort to cut polands debt owed to 
other governments 
reducing the debt burden is critical for poland to keep 
political support for its crash program to replace four decades of 
communism with a freemarket economy he said 
</TEXT>
